definition.value: A neutral group having formal unit electrical charges of opposite sign on non-adjacent atoms.
A cationic group that contains carbon.
A cationic group that contains no carbon.
An anionic phospholipid obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH group of any 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-1D-myo-inositol; major species at pH 7.3.
An N-acyl-L-alpha-amino acid anion that is the anion formed by loss of a proton from the carboxy group of N-carbamoyl-L-cysteine; major species present at pH 7.3.
A 2-amino-Delta(2)-thiazoline-4-carboxylic acid that has R configuration.
A 2-amino-Delta(2)-thiazoline-4-carboxylic acid that has S configuration.
An anionic group that contains carbon.
An anionic group that contains no carbon.
A 1,3-thiazole that is 4,5-dihydro-1,3-thiazole which is substituted at positions 2 and 4 by an amino and a carboxy group, respectively.
A 2-amino-Delta(2)-thiazoline-4-carboxylic acid zwitterion that has S-configuration. The major species at pH 7.3.
An amino acid zwitterion obtained from 2-amino-Delta(2)-thiazoline-4-carboxylic acid by the transfer of a proton from the carboxy group to the thiazoline nitrogen. The major species at pH 7.3.
A 2-amino-Delta(2)-thiazoline-4-carboxylic acid zwitterion that has R-configuration. The major species at pH 7.3.
An anionic phospholipid obtained by deprotonation of both phosphate OH groups of 3-heptaprenyl-sn-glycero-1-phosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of (+)-artemisinic acid. The major species at pH 7.3.

A monocarboxylic acid that is prop-2-en-1-ol acid which is substituted at position 2 by a 4,7-dimethyl-1,2,3,4,4a,5,6,8a-octahydronaphthalen-1-yl group (the 1S,4R,4aS,8aR diastereoisomer). It is a sesquiterpenoid precursor of artemisinin, obtained from sweet wormwood, Artemisia annua.
The acyl-CoA oxoanion resulting from the removal of all four protons from the phosphate groups of [(1R)-2,2,3-trimethyl-5-oxocyclopent-3-enyl]acetyl-CoA. Major species at pH 7.3.
An acyl-CoA(4-) oxoanion arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of [(2R)-3,3,4-trimethyl-6-oxo-3,6-dihydro-1H-pyran-2-yl]acetyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
A 6-hydroxycamphor that is (+)-camphor bearing a 6-exo-hydroxy substituent.
A 6-hydroxycamphor that is (+)-camphor bearing a 6-endo-hydroxy substituent.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3,4-dihydro-4-hydroxyphenylpyruvic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-(4-hydroxycyclohex-2-en-1-ylidene)pyruvic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of tetrahydro-4-hydroxyphenylpyruvic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of tetrahydrotyrosine; major species at pH 7.3.
A carotenoid ether that is (3E,3'E)-1,1'-dihydroxy-3,3',4,4'-tetradehydro-1,1',2,2'-tetrahydro-psi,psi-carotene-2-one in which both hydroxyl hydrogens are substituted by methyl groups.
A carotenoid ether that is (3E,3'E)-1,1'-dihydroxy-3,3',4,4'-tetradehydro-1,1',2,2'-tetrahydro-psi,psi-carotene-2,2'-dione in which both hydroxyl hydrogens are substituted by methyl groups.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of both phosphate OH groups of salicin-6-phosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
An anionic phospholipid obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups and protonation of the amino group of phytosphingosine 1-phosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
A tetrahydroxycyclohexanone that is cyclohexanone having four hydroxy groups located at positions 2, 3, 4 and 5 (the 2S,3R,4S,5R-diastereomer).
A sesquiterpene that is 1,2,4a,5,6,8a-hexahydronaphthalene which is substituted at position 1 by an isopropyl group and at positions 4 and 7 by methyl groups (the 1S,4aS,8aR-diastereoisomer).
A sesquiterpene that is 1,2,3,4,4a,5,6,8a-octahydronaphthalene which is substituted at positions 1, 4 and 7 respetively by isopropyl, methylene and methyl groups (the 1S,4aS,8aR-diastereoisomer).
A sesquiterpene that is tricyclo[4.4.0.0(2,7)]decane bearing methyl, isopropyl and methylene substituents at positions 1, 8 and 3 respectively (the 1S,6S,7S,8S-diastereomer)
A sesquiterpene that is octahydro-1H-1,4-methanoindene bearing methyl, isopropyl and methylene substituents at positions 4, 7 and 8 respectively (the 1R,3aS,4R,7R,7aR-isomer).
A sesquarterpene that is 1,4-cyclohexadiene bearing a methyl substituent at position 1 and a 6,10,14,18,22-pentamethyltricosa-5,9,13,17,21-pentaen-2-yl group at position 4.
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of L-histidinal, arising from protonation of the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
A phenol that is 2-phenylethanol in which the phenyl ring is substituted at position 2 by a hydroxy group.
Any terpene having a 35-carbon skeleton.
A 2-demethylmenaquinol having a side chain composed of seven isoprenoid units.
An alpha-amino acid that is alanine substituted at position 3 by a 4-hydroxycyclohex-2-en-1-yl group
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is pyruvic acid substituted at position 3 by a 4-hydroxycyclohex-2-en-1-yl group
Any hydroxycyclohexanone bearing four hydroxy substituents.
A benzoic acid in which any two of the ring hydrogens are substituted by methyl groups.
A dimethylbenzoic acid in which the two methyl groups are located at positions 2 and 4.
A dimethylbenzoate in which the two methyl groups are located at positions 2 and 4.
A benzoate obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any dimethylbenzoic acid.
A cyclic monoterpene ketone that is camphor bearing a hydroxy substituent at position 6.
A 4-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of [(R)-2,2,3-trimethyl-5-oxocyclopent-3-enyl]acetic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An anthracycline cation that is the conjugate acid of doxorubicin, arising from protonation of the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
An optically active form of (2,2,3-trimethyl-5-oxocyclopent-3-en-1-yl)acetic acid having R-configuration.
